            "content": "# Other apps\n\n_Active contributors: Alvin Sng, factory-octavian, David Vendrow, factory-sherry, factory-jerry_\n\nThis page covers the smaller and supporting apps in `apps/` that each deserve a brief explanation but don't warrant a full dedicated page.\n\n---\n\n## Signal\n\n**Path**: `apps/signal/`\n\n`apps/signal` is a GCP Cloud Function (`runSignalProcessor`) that processes behavioral signals collected about Droid usage. It is deployed via `@google-cloud/functions-framework`.\n\nThe function accepts a JSON body with a `mode` field and dispatches to one of four modes:\n\n| Mode | Description |\n|------|-------------|\n| `SubmitBatch` | Submits signal data batches for async BigQuery processing |\n| `ProcessResults` | Retrieves and processes completed batch results from BigQuery |\n| `DailyReport` | Queries BigQuery for the previous day's signal data, formats a summary, and posts it to Slack |\n| `AnalyzeAndTicket` | Runs a Droid agent to analyze signals and automatically create Linear tickets for detected issues |\n\nKey source files:\n- `src/index.ts` — HTTP entry point and mode dispatch\n- `src/core/` — BigQuery query logic (`bigquery.ts`) and batch runner (`runner.ts`)\n- `src/droid-analysis.ts` — Runs the Droid agent for the `AnalyzeAndTicket` mode\n- `src/report.ts` — Formats the daily Slack report\n- `src/signals/` — Signal type definitions\n\nSignal schemas are defined in the shared `@factory/signal-core` package.\n\n---\n\n## Functions\n\n**Path**: `apps/functions/`\n\n`apps/functions` contains Firebase Cloud Functions (v2) deployed to Firebase.\n\n| Function | Description |\n|----------|-------------|\n| `logDrainVercel` | Receives Vercel log drain webhooks, parses log entries, and routes them to the correct Axiom dataset (`AXIOM_DATASET_LOGS` or `AXIOM_DATASET_METRICS`). Verifies ownership via a public token in the response header. |\n| `indexSessionMessage` | Indexes session messages into a full-text search index for Algolia-based session search. |\n\nKey source files:\n- `src/logDrainVercel.ts` — Vercel log drain handler; extracts metrics logs by prefix and routes to Axiom\n- `src/sessionSearchIndex.ts` — Session message indexing\n- `src/index.ts` — Exports both functions as the Firebase entry points\n\n---\n\n## Scripts\n\n**Path**: `apps/scripts/`\n\n`apps/scripts` is a collection of standalone TypeScript scripts for operational and engineering tasks. Scripts are organized by concern in `src/`:\n\n| Script group | Description |\n|-------------|-------------|\n| `release/` | Release automation (version bumps, changelogs) |\n| `migrations/` | One-off data migration scripts |\n| `cancel-duplicate-subscriptions/` | Billing maintenance: find and cancel duplicate Orb subscriptions |\n| `download-bug-report/` | Download CLI bug reports from S3 for analysis |\n| `download-axiom-monitors/` | Export Axiom monitor configs |\n| `empty-files/` | Utility to find/handle empty files |\n| `readiness-benchmarks/` | Run agent readiness benchmarks |\n| `remote-droid-push/` | Push code changes to a remote Droid environment |\n| `remote-update-server/` | Manage the remote update server |\n| `resume-sandbox/` | Resume a stopped E2B sandbox |\n| `find-and-run-test-watch/` | Utility for test watching |\n\nScripts are typically run directly with Bun or Node: `bun apps/scripts/src/<name>/index.ts`.\n\n---\n\n## Relay {#relay}\n\n**Path**: `apps/relay/`\n\n`apps/relay` is a lightweight Bun WebSocket relay service for BYOI (Bring Your Own Infrastructure) computer sessions. It multiplexes N browser client connections onto a single daemon/agent connection per compute target.\n\n```\nBrowser ──WS──▶ Relay ◀──WS── Daemon\n(client)        │   ▲         (agent/computer)\n                └───┘\n           ChannelSession\n           (envelope mux/demux)\n```\n\n| Endpoint | Description |\n|----------|-------------|\n| `WS /v0/computer/:computerId/agent` | Daemon connects here (one per channel) |\n| `WS /v0/computer/:computerId/client` | Browser clients connect here (N per channel) |\n| `GET /health` | Health check |\n\nClients are rejected with 503 if no agent is connected for the requested `computerId`. The envelope protocol schemas live in `@factory/common/relay`; codec functions in `@factory/utils/relay`.\n\nKey components in `src/`:\n- `server.ts` — `RelayServer`: Bun HTTP + WebSocket server\n- `channel/` — `ChannelSession` (per-computer mux/demux) and `ChannelRegistry` (in-memory lookup)\n\nThe relay is started with `--remote-access` flag passed to `droid daemon` (see [apps/desktop.md](./desktop.md)). See also [apps/daemon.md](./daemon.md).\n\n---\n\n## JetBrains plugin {#jetbrains-plugin}\n\n**Path**: `apps/factory-jetbrains-plugin/`\n\n`apps/factory-jetbrains-plugin` is a Kotlin/Gradle plugin for IntelliJ IDEA, WebStorm, PyCharm, and other JetBrains IDEs. It mirrors the VS Code extension: launching the Droid CLI in an embedded terminal and sharing IDE context with it over MCP.\n\nBuilt with the IntelliJ Platform Plugin SDK (Gradle). Minimum IDE version: 2023.1.\n\nKey components (in `src/main/kotlin/`):\n- `RunFactoryDroidAction` — Toolbar action that opens the IDE terminal with `droid`\n- `MCPServerService` — HTTP MCP server (same protocol as VS Code extension)\n- `OpenFilesManager` — Tracks open files and selections\n- `DiagnosticsManager` — Collects IDE inspections and compiler errors\n- `DiffManager` — Shows proposed diffs in IntelliJ's diff viewer\n\nThe CLI discovers the MCP server via `FACTORY_JETBRAINS_MCP_PORT` environment variable set when launching the terminal.\n\nBuild: `./gradlew buildPlugin`. Output: `build/distributions/*.zip`.\n\n---\n\n## Storybook {#storybook}\n\n**Path**: `apps/storybook/`\n\n`apps/storybook` hosts a Storybook 8 instance for developing and previewing `@factory/core-ui` components in isolation. It runs on port 6006 and is included in the `dev:web` target.\n\n```bash\nnpm run dev --filter=storybook   # start on :6006\nnpm run build --filter=storybook # build static output\n```\n\nStories live in `packages/core-ui/src/` alongside the components they document. The storybook app itself (`apps/storybook/`) is minimal — it just provides the Storybook shell, `.storybook/` config, and a `scripts/run-bin.cjs` helper for monorepo-compatible binary resolution.\n\n---\n\n## Bridge\n\n**Path**: `apps/bridge/`\n\nCurrently an empty placeholder directory. No source files.\n\n---\n\n## Migrations\n\n**Path**: `apps/migrations/`\n\nCurrently an empty placeholder directory. Active migration scripts live in `apps/scripts/src/migrations/`.\n",
