            "content": "# API overview\n\nFactory exposes APIs at several layers. Clients (CLI, web, desktop) primarily talk to the **daemon** over WebSocket JSON-RPC. The daemon and all clients call the **backend REST API** over HTTPS. LLM traffic goes through the backend's **LLM proxy**. Persistent data lives in **Firebase/Firestore**, accessed only by the backend.\n\n## APIs at a glance\n\n| API | Transport | Auth | Consumers |\n|-----|-----------|------|-----------|\n| [Backend REST API](rest-endpoints.md) | HTTPS REST | WorkOS Bearer token or Factory API key | CLI, daemon, web, desktop |\n| [Daemon WebSocket JSON-RPC](../apps/daemon.md) | WebSocket (JSON-RPC 2.0) | Daemon token (short-lived, issued by backend) | CLI, web, desktop |\n| LLM proxy (part of backend) | HTTPS streaming | WorkOS Bearer token | CLI, daemon |\n| Firebase/Firestore | Firebase SDK / REST | Firebase service account | Backend only |\n\n## Communication flow\n\n```mermaid\ngraph LR\n    CLI[\"Droid CLI\"]\n    Web[\"Web / Desktop\"]\n    Daemon[\"factoryd daemon\"]\n    Backend[\"Backend API\\n(Next.js / Vercel)\"]\n    LLMs[\"LLM providers\"]\n    Firebase[\"Firebase / Firestore\"]\n\n    CLI -->|\"WebSocket JSON-RPC\"| Daemon\n    Web -->|\"WebSocket JSON-RPC\"| Daemon\n    Daemon -->|\"HTTPS REST\"| Backend\n    CLI -->|\"HTTPS REST\"| Backend\n    Backend -->|\"HTTPS streaming\"| LLMs\n    Backend -->|\"Firestore SDK\"| Firebase\n```\n\n## Backend REST API\n\nAll routes live under `apps/backend/src/app/api/`. They are served from Vercel and follow Next.js App Router conventions. See [rest-endpoints.md](rest-endpoints.md) for a table of route groups and their purposes.\n\nAuthentication for most routes uses a `WorkOS` access token passed as `Authorization: Bearer <token>`. Internal service-to-service routes accept Factory API keys (`fk_…`). Admin routes use separate AWS Secrets Manager–stored API keys. See [security.md](../security.md) for details.\n\n## Daemon WebSocket JSON-RPC API\n\n`factoryd` (the daemon) exposes a local WebSocket server. Clients connect, authenticate once with a short-lived token, then send JSON-RPC 2.0 requests. The daemon responds synchronously and also sends unsolicited notifications (e.g. `daemon.session_notification`).\n\nProtocol types are defined in `packages/common/src/daemon/`. Method names are grouped into three enums:\n\n- `DaemonConnectionMethod` — connection lifecycle (`daemon.authenticate`)\n- `DaemonDroidMethod` — session and AI operations (`daemon.initialize_session`, `daemon.add_user_message`, `daemon.interrupt_session`, …)\n- `DaemonTerminalMethod` — terminal multiplexer (`daemon.create_terminal`, `daemon.write_terminal_data`, …)\n\nSee [apps/daemon.md](../apps/daemon.md) for full protocol documentation.\n\n## LLM proxy\n\nRoutes under `/api/llm/` receive requests from clients, normalise them to provider format, stream responses back via SSE, and record token-usage metrics. Provider backends include Anthropic, OpenAI, Google Vertex AI, AWS Bedrock, Fireworks, Baseten, and xAI. See [apps/backend.md](../apps/backend.md) for details.\n\n## Firebase / Firestore\n\nFirestore is the primary datastore for sessions, organisations, users, and billing data. It is not directly accessible by clients — all reads and writes go through the backend API. Firebase Auth is not used for user authentication; that role belongs to WorkOS.\n",
