            "content": "# Security\n\n## Authentication\n\n### User authentication (WorkOS)\n\nEnd-user authentication is handled by [WorkOS](https://workos.com). The frontend exchanges credentials for a short-lived WorkOS access token, which is included on every API request as `Authorization: Bearer <token>`.\n\nThe backend verifies the token in `apps/backend/src/app/api/_utils/middleware.ts` (`verifyUser`):\n\n1. If the `Authorization` header contains a token starting with `fk_`, it is treated as a **Factory API key** and verified against Firestore via `verifyFactoryApiKey`.\n2. Otherwise, the token is verified as a **WorkOS access token** using `verifyWorkOSAccessToken`.\n3. The resolved user object (`WorkOSUserWithClaims`) carries `firestoreOrgId`, `workosOrgId`, and `role`.\n\nUnauthenticated requests to protected routes receive `401 Unauthorized`. Authenticated users lacking the required role receive `403 Forbidden`.\n\n### Service-to-service authentication\n\n- **Admin routes** use static API keys stored in AWS Secrets Manager (accessed via `getAdminApiKeys`). The key is compared with the `Authorization` header using a constant-time comparison.\n- **Cron routes** verify a `CRON_SECRET` environment variable injected by Vercel.\n- **Webhook routes** verify inbound signatures from external services (Orb HMAC, WorkOS webhook signature, etc.).\n- **Daemon ↔ backend** uses short-lived daemon tokens issued by the backend at connection time.\n\n## Authorisation\n\nRole-based access control uses `WorkosMembershipRole` values (`User`, `Admin`, `Owner`). The role is stored in the user's Firestore profile and surfaced via the WorkOS token claims. `handleRouteMiddleware` checks `hasAdequateRolePrivilege` before dispatching to the route handler.\n\nOrganisation-level deactivation is also checked: a `401` is returned if the org is flagged as deactivated.\n\n## CORS and security headers\n\nThe Next.js middleware in `apps/backend/src/middleware.ts` runs on every request at the Vercel Edge. It:\n\n- Validates the `Origin` header against an allowlist (exact matches and wildcard patterns via `createOriginValidator`).\n- On allowed origins, sets `Access-Control-Allow-Origin`, `Access-Control-Allow-Credentials: true`, and `Vary: Origin`.\n- On all responses, sets the following security headers:\n\n| Header | Value |\n|--------|-------|\n| `X-Content-Type-Options` | `nosniff` |\n| `Content-Security-Policy` | Full CSP (see `apps/backend/src/constants.ts`) |\n| `Permissions-Policy` | Restricts camera, geolocation, and browsing-topics |\n| `Referrer-Policy` | `strict-origin` |\n| `Cross-Origin-Opener-Policy` | `same-origin` |\n| `Cross-Origin-Embedder-Policy` | `credentialless` |\n| `Server` | `` (cleared) |\n\n## Rate limiting\n\nRate limiting is enforced at the application layer for API-key-accessible routes using Vercel Firewall rules, called via `@vercel/firewall`:\n\n- `LLM_PROXY` — per-user and per-org limits on LLM proxy calls.\n- `SUBSCRIPTION` — per-org limits on subscription management routes.\n- `ANALYTICS_API` — per-org limits on analytics API calls.\n\nRate-limit identifiers and category mappings are in `apps/backend/src/app/api/_utils/rate-limit.ts`. Exceeded limits return `429 Too Many Requests`.\n\n## Input validation\n\nAll external inputs are validated with [Zod](https://zod.dev) schemas before reaching business logic. Schema definitions live alongside their types, typically in `packages/common/src/api/` and `packages/common/src/daemon/schemas/`. Request bodies, URL parameters, and webhook payloads are all parsed through Zod.\n\nRoutes that receive invalid input return `400 Bad Request` via `ResponseError400BadRequest`.\n\n## Secrets management\n\nSecrets are never hardcoded. They are stored in:\n\n- **Vercel environment variables** — for backend/web/admin at deploy time.\n- **AWS Secrets Manager** — for admin API keys and third-party service credentials accessed at runtime via `@factory/services/aws/secrets`.\n- **GitHub Actions secrets** — for CI/CD workflows (deployment tokens, signing certificates, etc.).\n\nThe `@factory/utils/secretScrubber` utility (`scrubSecrets`, `scrubbed`) is applied to all log metadata before it is written to stdout or sent to Sentry, preventing accidental credential leakage in logs.\n\n## Trust boundaries\n\n```mermaid\ngraph LR\n    Browser[\"Browser / Desktop / CLI\\n(untrusted)\"]\n    Backend[\"Backend API\\n(trusted: Vercel)\"]\n    Daemon[\"factoryd\\n(trusted: user's machine)\"]\n    Firebase[\"Firebase\\n(trusted: GCP)\"]\n    LLMs[\"LLM providers\\n(external)\"]\n\n    Browser -->|\"WorkOS token\"| Backend\n    Daemon -->|\"Daemon token\"| Backend\n    Backend -->|\"Service account\"| Firebase\n    Backend -->|\"API keys\"| LLMs\n```\n\nThe daemon runs on the user's own machine and is considered trusted from the user's perspective. Backend routes that the daemon calls still require a valid daemon token.\n\nThe browser and CLI are always untrusted — all tokens are short-lived and verified on each request.\n\n## Related pages\n\n- [API endpoints](api/rest-endpoints.md)\n- [Backend app](apps/backend.md)\n- [Error handling patterns](how-to-contribute/patterns-and-conventions.md)\n- [Reference: environment variables](reference/configuration.md)\n",
