            "content": "# Logging\n\n## Package\n\nAll logging goes through `@factory/logging` (`packages/logging/src/`). Import from the package root:\n\n```ts\nimport { logInfo, logWarn, logException } from '@factory/logging';\n```\n\nNever use `console.log` / `console.error` directly in production code — they bypass secret scrubbing and Sentry integration.\n\n## Log functions\n\n### `logInfo(message, metadata?)`\n\nInformational messages. Also adds a Sentry breadcrumb (`type: 'debug'`).\n\n```ts\nlogInfo('Session started', { sessionId, userId });\n```\n\n### `logWarn(message, metadata?)`\n\nWarnings that don't break functionality. Adds a Sentry breadcrumb (`level: 'warning'`).\n\n```ts\nlogWarn('LLM rate limit approaching', { usage: 950, limit: 1000 });\n```\n\n### `logException(error, message, metadata?, options?)`\n\nErrors inside a `catch` block. Captures to Sentry and prints the full stack chain.\n\n```ts\ntry {\n  await riskyOp();\n} catch (error) {\n  logException(error, 'Failed to run risky operation', { userId });\n  // Do NOT rethrow after logException — it handles the error here.\n}\n```\n\n`logException` does **not** rethrow. If you want to propagate the error, throw it without calling `logException` (the middleware will log it at the boundary). See the [error handling patterns](../how-to-contribute/patterns-and-conventions.md) for the full decision tree.\n\n`options.ignore400s: true` suppresses Sentry capture for 4xx errors, useful when the caller expects user errors and wants only 5xx exceptions to alert.\n\n### `logError(message, metadata?)` (rare)\n\nLogs a message-level error to Sentry without an exception object. Prefer `logException` when an `Error` is available.\n\n## Metadata\n\nPass a `LogMetadata` object as the second argument. Keys are attached as Sentry tags and included in the structured JSON log line. Avoid nesting deep objects — prefer flat key-value pairs.\n\nKeys `body`, `error`, `errorMessage`, `messages`, and `headers` are automatically scrubbed for secrets before being logged or sent to Sentry.\n\n## Secret scrubbing\n\n`@factory/utils/secretScrubber` (`scrubSecrets`) scans strings for patterns that look like API keys, tokens, or passwords and replaces them with `[REDACTED]`. This runs automatically inside all `log*` functions. You do not need to manually redact values before logging.\n\n## Output format\n\nIn server-side and CLI/daemon environments, `defaultLogToConsole` (`packages/logging/src/defaultLogToConsole.ts`) formats output via [pino](https://getpino.io) as newline-delimited JSON:\n\n```json\n{\"level\":\"info\",\"msg\":\"Session started\",\"sessionId\":\"abc123\",\"userId\":\"u_456\",\"tags\":{}}\n```\n\nThe `level` key uses the string label (`info`, `warn`, `error`).\n\nIn browser environments, logs go to the browser console in non-production mode and are batched into the `TelemetryClient` for ingest by the backend `/api/telemetry/` endpoint.\n\n## Sentry integration\n\nSentry is initialised at startup in each component. The adapter is registered globally via `setSentryAdapter(Sentry)` from `@factory/logging/sentry`. Once registered, `logException` captures exceptions to Sentry automatically.\n\nSentry is enabled when `SENTRY_DSN` is set. The `isSentryEnabled()` helper checks for this. All Sentry calls are guarded by this flag so the code path is a no-op in local development by default.\n\nRequest context (user ID, org ID, session ID, client type) is attached to the Sentry scope in `configureSentry` inside the middleware utilities.\n\n## Log file locations\n\nIn local development, logs go to stdout. When running via `npm run dev:web`, each app streams to a log file:\n\n| App | Log file |\n|-----|----------|\n| Backend | `/tmp/factory-dev-backend.log` |\n| Admin | `/tmp/factory-dev-admin.log` |\n| Daemon | `/tmp/factory-dev-daemon.log` |\n| Desktop | `/tmp/factory-dev-desktop.log` |\n\nFor CLI/daemon in dev, logs are also written to `~/.factory-dev/logs/`.\n\nUse `tail -f /tmp/factory-dev-backend.log` to stream logs in real time.\n\n## Request context (AsyncLocalStorage)\n\n`runRequestStore` / `getRequestStore` from `packages/logging/src/requestLocal.ts` uses Node's `AsyncLocalStorage` to attach per-request context (org ID, session ID, trace ID) to every log line emitted within a request handler, without needing to thread it through function arguments.\n\n## Adding a log statement\n\n1. Import `logInfo`, `logWarn`, or `logException` from `@factory/logging`.\n2. Pick the right level: `logInfo` for normal flow, `logWarn` for degraded-but-recoverable states, `logException` inside catch blocks where you handle the error locally.\n3. Include relevant metadata as flat key-value pairs.\n4. Do not include secrets or raw request bodies — they are scrubbed automatically, but keeping them out of metadata is still preferred.\n\n## Related pages\n\n- [Monitoring overview](index.md)\n- [Metrics](metrics.md)\n- [Error handling patterns](../how-to-contribute/patterns-and-conventions.md)\n",
