            "content": "# Metrics\n\n## Overview\n\nCustom metrics are recorded via the `Metrics` class in `packages/logging/src/metrics.ts`. On the server side (backend, daemon, CLI), each metric call emits a structured JSON log line prefixed with `[metric:`. Axiom ingests these lines and makes them queryable. On the browser/client side, metrics are batched through `TelemetryClient` and sent to the backend `/api/telemetry/` ingest endpoint.\n\n## API\n\nImport `Metrics` from `@factory/logging`:\n\n```ts\nimport { Metrics } from '@factory/logging';\n```\n\n### `Metrics.addToCounter(name, value, labels?)`\n\nIncrement a counter. Typical value is `1`.\n\n```ts\nMetrics.addToCounter('llm_completion_success_count', 1, { model: 'claude-3-5-sonnet', provider: 'anthropic' });\n```\n\n### `Metrics.setGauge(name, value, labels?)`\n\nRecord a point-in-time value (e.g. queue depth, active connections).\n\n```ts\nMetrics.setGauge('active_sessions_count', 42);\n```\n\n### `Metrics.recordHistogram(name, value, labels?)`\n\nRecord a distribution sample (latency, sizes).\n\n```ts\nMetrics.recordHistogram('session_initialize_latency_ms', 1250, { sessionType: 'local' });\n```\n\n## Metric labels\n\nLabels are key-value pairs attached to a metric call for filtering and grouping in Axiom. Common label keys are defined in the `MetricLabels` type in `packages/logging/src/metrics/types.ts` and include:\n\n- `model` — LLM model identifier\n- `provider` — LLM provider name\n- `status` — `success` or `error`\n- `integrationType` — integration name (e.g. `github`, `linear`)\n\nUse consistent label names to enable cross-query grouping.\n\n## Instrumenting external dependencies\n\nThe backend provides `fetchWithMetrics` and `callWithMetrics` helpers in `apps/backend/src/app/api/_utils/metrics/` to automatically record latency, success/error counts, and labels for external service calls:\n\n```ts\nimport { fetchWithMetrics } from '@/app/api/_utils/metrics';\nimport { ExternalDependency } from '@/app/api/_utils/metrics/enums';\n\nconst response = await fetchWithMetrics(\n  fetch,\n  ExternalDependency.OPENAI,\n  { labels: { model: 'gpt-4' } },\n  'https://api.openai.com/v1/chat/completions',\n  { method: 'POST', body: JSON.stringify(payload) }\n);\n```\n\n`ExternalDependency` is an enum in `apps/backend/src/app/api/_utils/metrics/enums.ts`. Add new external services there when adding integrations.\n\n## Naming conventions\n\n- Use `snake_case`.\n- Suffix counters with `_count` (e.g. `llm_completion_error_count`).\n- Suffix latency histograms with `_ms` (e.g. `request_latency_ms`).\n- Suffix size histograms with `_bytes` (e.g. `response_size_bytes`).\n- Include the unit in the name — do not rely on documentation to convey it.\n\n## Viewing metrics in Axiom\n\nMetrics are stored as regular log events in Axiom alongside structured logs. To query a metric:\n\n1. Open the Axiom dataset that receives backend/daemon/CLI logs.\n2. Filter for log lines where the `msg` field starts with `[metric:`.\n3. Use the `metric` field to filter by name and `value` to aggregate.\n\nExample APL (Axiom Processing Language) query:\n\n```\n['backend-logs']\n| where msg startswith \"[metric:\"\n| where metric == \"llm_completion_success_count\"\n| summarize count = sum(value) by bin(_time, 5m), model\n```\n\n## OpenTelemetry traces (backend)\n\nThe backend supports distributed tracing via OpenTelemetry when `FACTORY_OTEL_ENABLED=true`. Traces are exported to Axiom via OTLP HTTP. The Axiom dataset and endpoint are configured in `apps/backend/src/app/api/telemetry/otlp/traces/constants.ts`.\n\n`OtelTracing.trace()` from `@factory/logging/tracing` wraps a block of code in a span. Trace context (trace ID, span ID) is automatically included in pino log lines via the Sentry active span context.\n\n## Sentry performance monitoring\n\nSentry is used primarily for error tracking. It does not receive custom metric data, but does receive transaction and span data through the `@sentry/nextjs` auto-instrumentation on the backend.\n\n## Related pages\n\n- [Monitoring overview](index.md)\n- [Logging](logging.md)\n",
