            "content": "# Design decisions and background\n\nThis page documents key architectural decisions made during Factory's development — why certain technologies were chosen and what alternatives were considered.\n\n## Why Bun for CLI and daemon\n\nThe CLI (`apps/cli`) and daemon (`apps/daemon`) both run on [Bun](https://bun.sh) rather than Node.js. The main reasons:\n\n- **Startup speed**: Bun's JIT-compiled runtime starts significantly faster than Node.js. For a CLI tool, cold-start latency is user-visible.\n- **Single executable archives (SEA)**: Bun makes it straightforward to produce a single self-contained binary from a TypeScript source tree. The CLI build (`bun scripts/build-sea.ts`) produces a cross-platform binary that users can install without needing Node/npm. Node added SEA support later but it is less mature.\n- **Built-in bundler**: Bun's bundler (`bun scripts/bundle.ts`) handles the npm-publishable wrapper for the CLI without an additional tooling step.\n- **TypeScript natively**: Bun runs `.ts` files directly without a transpile step in development (`bun src/index.ts`), keeping the dev loop fast.\n- **`bun-pty`**: The pseudo-terminal library (`bun-pty`) is built specifically for Bun and provides stable PTY support for the daemon's terminal multiplexer.\n\nThe trade-off is that not all Node.js ecosystem libraries work out of the box on Bun. The team has occasionally hit compatibility issues with packages that rely on Node-specific internals, but these are typically resolvable.\n\n## Why Ink (React for terminal)\n\nThe CLI's interactive TUI is built with [Ink](https://github.com/vadimdemedes/ink) — a React renderer that targets terminal output instead of the DOM.\n\nReasons for Ink:\n\n- **React component model**: The team already writes React for the web and desktop frontends. Using the same mental model (components, hooks, state) for the terminal avoids a large context switch.\n- **Declarative rendering**: Ink handles diffing and re-rendering terminal output. Without it, managing escape codes, cursor positioning, and partial redraws manually would be error-prone.\n- **Composability**: Complex TUI layouts (split panes, scrollable lists, status bars) can be built from small composable components rather than imperative `process.stdout.write` calls.\n- **Testing**: `ink-testing-library` (a dependency in `apps/cli/package.json`) provides snapshot and interaction testing for terminal components, making it possible to write unit tests for the TUI.\n\nThe alternative would have been a library like `blessed` or raw ANSI manipulation. Both are harder to maintain and don't compose as well.\n\n## Why JSON-RPC 2.0 for the daemon protocol\n\nThe frontend ↔ daemon communication uses [JSON-RPC 2.0](https://www.jsonrpc.org/specification) over WebSocket. This was chosen because:\n\n- **Standard request/response + notifications**: JSON-RPC has a well-defined wire format for both request–response pairs (with matching `id` fields) and one-way server notifications (no `id`). The daemon needs both — clients send method calls and the daemon pushes streaming session notifications. JSON-RPC covers both without a bespoke protocol.\n- **Typed schema**: All method names, request params, and result shapes are defined as Zod schemas in `packages/common/src/daemon/`. This creates a single source of truth shared across all clients (CLI, web, desktop), enforced at the TypeScript level.\n- **Toolability**: Being a standard protocol means tooling (debugging proxies, mock servers, test harnesses) is readily available.\n- **Simplicity**: Compared to alternatives like gRPC (which would require protobuf tooling and binary encoding) or a bespoke WebSocket protocol, JSON-RPC is easy to implement and debug. The messages are readable JSON.\n\nThe enum of method names (`DaemonDroidMethod`, `DaemonTerminalMethod`, `DaemonConnectionMethod` in `packages/common/src/daemon/schemas/enums.ts`) serves as the protocol's API surface.\n\n## Why Turborepo\n\nThe monorepo uses [Turborepo](https://turbo.build/repo) for task orchestration. Reasons:\n\n- **Incremental builds with remote caching**: Turbo caches build, test, lint, and typecheck outputs by content hash. On CI, unchanged packages skip their tasks entirely, significantly reducing pipeline time in a monorepo with ~20 packages and apps.\n- **Dependency-aware task graphs**: `turbo.json` (at the repo root) declares task dependencies (e.g. `build` depends on dependencies' `build`). Turbo computes the correct execution order automatically.\n- **Parallel execution**: Independent tasks run in parallel up to the configured concurrency limit.\n- **Filtering**: `--filter=@factory/frontend` runs tasks only for the specified package and its dependents/dependencies, enabling targeted CI runs (see `.github/workflows/check-affected.yml`).\n\nThe alternative for task ordering would be a hand-rolled Makefile or shell scripts. Turbo's content-hash caching is the primary reason it was chosen — it makes `npm run test` or `npm run build` on a large PR much faster because only affected packages need to run.\n\n## Why WorkOS for authentication\n\n[WorkOS](https://workos.com) is used for user authentication and organisation management. Reasons:\n\n- **Enterprise SSO out of the box**: WorkOS provides SAML/OIDC SSO, SCIM directory sync, and audit logs without requiring Factory to implement them. These are table-stakes features for enterprise customers.\n- **Organisation management**: WorkOS models the concept of organisations, memberships, and roles natively. This maps directly to how Factory organises teams.\n- **Managed identity provider integrations**: WorkOS connects to Okta, Azure AD, Google Workspace, and others. Factory teams can sign in with their existing IdP without configuration work on Factory's side.\n- **Hosted auth UI**: WorkOS provides a hosted login flow, reducing the surface area Factory needs to secure and maintain.\n\nThe alternative was building SSO/SCIM support on top of a lower-level auth library (e.g. Passport.js). WorkOS significantly reduces that engineering burden, at the cost of a vendor dependency.\n\n## Related pages\n\n- [System architecture](../overview/architecture.md)\n- [Daemon WebSocket server](../apps/daemon.md)\n- [Backend API](../apps/backend.md)\n",
