            "content": "# Sessions\n\n**Active contributors**: factory-sherry, Luke Alvoeiro, factory-octavian, Andrei Savin, Ricky S, shashank-factory\n\n## Purpose\n\nA session is the unit of continuity in Droid. It holds the complete conversation history between the user and the agent, the settings in effect for that conversation (model, autonomy level, interaction mode), and accumulated token usage. Sessions persist across CLI restarts and can be resumed, forked, or searched.\n\nFor implementation details see [apps/cli/session-management.md](../apps/cli/session-management.md).\n\n## Creating a session\n\nA new session starts whenever `droid` launches without a `--resume` flag. Each session gets a UUID and is written immediately to disk as a JSONL file. The session title is auto-generated after the first exchange with the agent.\n\nIn **exec mode** (`droid exec \"...\"`) a session is created implicitly, runs to completion, and the session ID is printed at the end for later resume.\n\n## On-disk storage\n\nSessions are stored as [JSONL](https://jsonlines.org/) files under `~/.factory/sessions/`:\n\n```\n~/.factory/sessions/\n├── <session-id>.jsonl            # global (project-agnostic) session\n├── -<sanitized-cwd>/             # project-scoped directory\n│   ├── <session-id>.jsonl\n│   └── <session-id>.settings.json\n└── .favorites                    # set of favorited session IDs\n```\n\n**Line 1** of every `.jsonl` file is a `SessionSummaryEvent` with metadata (id, title, cwd, tags, owner). **Subsequent lines** are `DroidMessageEvent` records, one per conversation turn.\n\nPDF attachments are stored separately at `~/.factory/sessions/<session-id>/attachments/`.\n\nThe directory is created with `chmod 700` to prevent other local users from reading conversation history.\n\n## Resuming a session\n\nPass `--resume` (most recent session) or `--resume <session-id>` (specific session) to continue a previous conversation. Inside the TUI, `/sessions` opens a searchable picker showing all sessions sorted by last-modified time.\n\nIn exec mode pass `--session-id <id>` to attach to an existing session.\n\n## Forking\n\n`/fork` (or `/rewind`) creates a copy of the current session truncated at a specific message. This is useful when the agent took a wrong turn — fork at the last good message and try a different prompt. The forked session records its `parentSessionId` for traceability.\n\n## Searching sessions\n\n`/sessions` in the TUI provides a fuzzy-search overlay. The CLI pre-builds a search index at startup (`warmSearchCache`) from the first JSONL line of each session file so that search does not require loading full message histories.\n\n`droid sessions` (the top-level command) lists sessions from the command line.\n\n## Per-session settings\n\nEach session has a `SessionSettings` object persisted to `<session-id>.settings.json`:\n\n| Setting | What it controls |\n|---|---|\n| `model` | Active model ID (e.g., `claude-sonnet-4-6`) |\n| `reasoningEffort` | Thinking budget: off / low / medium / high / xhigh |\n| `interactionMode` | Auto / Spec / AGI (Mission) |\n| `autonomyLevel` | Off / Low / Medium / High — controls which tool categories run without confirmation |\n| `specModeModel` | Separate model used in Spec mode planning phase |\n\nSettings changes are saved to disk and optionally synced to the Factory API for cloud continuity.\n\n## Autonomy levels\n\nThe autonomy level controls how much the agent can do without pausing for permission:\n\n| Level | Behavior |\n|---|---|\n| Off | Read-only; no writes or executions |\n| Low | Runs safe commands; asks before writes |\n| Medium | Runs writes and shell commands in allowed patterns |\n| High | Runs most tools without confirmation |\n\nOrganization policies can cap the maximum level via `SettingsManager`. The agent never exceeds the org cap regardless of user preference.\n\n## Compaction\n\nWhen the conversation approaches the model's context limit, the session is automatically compacted:\n\n1. The older portion of the message history is summarized by the LLM.\n2. The full history is replaced with `[compact summary] + [recent messages]`.\n3. The compacted content is written back to the JSONL file.\n\nThis keeps sessions alive indefinitely without hitting provider token limits.\n\n## Cloud sync\n\nWhen connected to a Factory account, session creation, settings changes, and status updates are synced to the Factory API. This allows sessions started on the CLI to be visible in the web and desktop clients, and vice versa.\n\n## Integration points\n\n| Component | Relationship |\n|---|---|\n| [apps/cli/session-management.md](../apps/cli/session-management.md) | Full implementation details for `SessionService` |\n| [apps/daemon.md](../apps/daemon.md) | Daemon owns its own session lifecycle for web/desktop clients |\n| [features/missions.md](./missions.md) | Missions use orchestrator and worker sessions; session type is tracked in `decompSessionType` |\n| [packages/common.md](../packages/common.md) | Session types in `@factory/common/session` and `@factory/common/sessionV2` |\n",
