            "content": "# MCP integration\n\n**Active contributors**: factory-jerry, Alvin Sng, Qingchen Dang, David Vendrow, Arman Bolat, Varin Nair\n\n## Purpose\n\nModel Context Protocol (MCP) lets external servers provide tools and resources to the Droid agent. MCP tools complement [skills](./skills.md): where a skill injects instructions into the context, an MCP tool is a callable function the agent can invoke during a conversation — querying a database, running a shell command, fetching a URL, or interacting with a browser.\n\nFor implementation details see [apps/cli/mcp.md](../apps/cli/mcp.md).\n\n## What MCP enables\n\n- Connect Droid to any MCP-compatible tool server without modifying the CLI\n- Run browser automation (Playwright), database queries, GitHub API calls, search APIs, and more\n- Share tool servers across a team by committing `.factory/settings.json` to the repo\n- Subscribe to live resource updates (e.g., a file-watcher server pushing updated context into the agent)\n\n## Configuration\n\nMCP servers are configured in the `mcpServers` map inside `~/.factory/settings.json` (personal) or `<repo>/.factory/settings.json` (project):\n\n```jsonc\n{\n  \"mcpServers\": {\n    \"my-db\": {\n      \"type\": \"stdio\",\n      \"command\": \"npx\",\n      \"args\": [\"-y\", \"@my-org/mcp-db-server\"],\n      \"env\": { \"DB_URL\": \"postgres://...\" }\n    },\n    \"github\": {\n      \"type\": \"http\",\n      \"url\": \"https://api.github.com/mcp\",\n      \"headers\": { \"Authorization\": \"Bearer ghp_...\" }\n    }\n  }\n}\n```\n\nPer-server options:\n\n| Field | Default | Purpose |\n|---|---|---|\n| `type` | `stdio` | Transport: `stdio` (local process) or `http` (remote) |\n| `command` | — | Executable for stdio servers |\n| `args` | `[]` | Arguments for stdio servers |\n| `env` | `{}` | Environment overrides for the child process |\n| `url` | — | Endpoint URL for HTTP servers |\n| `headers` | `{}` | Extra request headers (e.g., auth tokens) |\n| `disabled` | `false` | Suppress startup without removing the entry |\n| `disabledTools` | `[]` | Block specific tools from this server |\n\n## Transport types\n\n**Stdio** — the most common type. The CLI spawns a child process (typically an `npx` package or a local script) and communicates over stdin/stdout using the MCP protocol. The child process inherits the current environment merged with any `env` overrides.\n\n**HTTP** — connects to a remote MCP endpoint. If the server requires OAuth, the CLI opens the authorization URL in the browser, starts a local callback server to receive the code, exchanges it for tokens, and persists them to `~/.factory/mcp-oauth/`.\n\n## Managing servers\n\n| Method | Effect |\n|---|---|\n| `droid mcp add <name> <url-or-command>` | Adds server to settings and triggers live reload |\n| `droid mcp remove <name>` | Removes server from settings |\n| `/mcp` (TUI) | Opens the interactive MCP manager overlay |\n\nThe interactive overlay shows connection status, lists tools per server, and lets you enable or disable individual tools without editing JSON.\n\n## Server lifecycle\n\n```mermaid\ngraph TD\n    A[CLI start] --> B[McpService.start]\n    B --> C[Load user + system configs]\n    C --> D[McpHub.reloadServers]\n    D --> E[Start HTTP servers sequentially]\n    D --> F[Start stdio servers in parallel]\n    E --> G[listAllTools]\n    F --> G\n    G --> H[Register each tool in TUI tool registry]\n    H --> I[Agent can call MCP tools]\n    I --> J{Settings change?}\n    J -- yes --> K[McpHub.reloadServers — diff configs]\n    K --> L[Stop removed/changed servers]\n    K --> M[Start new servers]\n    L --> H\n    M --> H\n```\n\nHTTP servers start sequentially to avoid OAuth callback port conflicts. Stdio servers start in parallel.\n\nWhen settings change on disk, `McpService` reloads only the servers whose configuration changed. Unchanged servers keep running without interruption.\n\n## System vs user servers\n\n`McpHub` distinguishes two server sets:\n- **System servers** — built-in, started alongside user servers and never stopped by config reloads. Currently this includes the internal CLI MCP server used for VS Code integration.\n- **User servers** — defined in `mcpServers` in settings, subject to live reload.\n\n## Tool naming\n\nEach MCP tool is exposed to the agent as `{serverName}_{toolName}`. This prefix prevents collisions across servers and lets the LLM identify which server provides each tool.\n\n## Integration points\n\n| Component | Relationship |\n|---|---|\n| [apps/cli/mcp.md](../apps/cli/mcp.md) | Full implementation details for `McpHub` and `McpService` |\n| [features/ide-integrations.md](./ide-integrations.md) | VS Code extension exposes an MCP server that the CLI connects to as a system server |\n| [features/skills.md](./skills.md) | Skills provide context; MCP tools provide callable functions |\n| `@modelcontextprotocol/sdk` | Official MCP TypeScript SDK used for all transport and protocol logic |\n",
