            "content": "# Feature flags\n\n**Active contributors**: l30t, Abhay Singhal, Luke Alvoeiro, jonathan-factory, Alvin Sng, David Vendrow\n\n## Purpose\n\nFeature flags control which capabilities are enabled for which users and organizations without requiring a code deploy. The platform uses [Statsig](https://statsig.com/) as the flag evaluation service. Flag definitions live in `@factory/common` so any app (CLI, web, backend) can reference the same registry.\n\nSee also `docs/feature-flags.md` for the team-facing how-to guide.\n\n## Defining a flag\n\nAll feature flags are registered in `packages/common/src/feature-flags/constants.ts` inside the `FactoryFeatureFlags` object:\n\n```typescript\nexport const FactoryFeatureFlags = {\n  // ...\n  Wiki: {\n    displayName: 'Wiki',\n    statsigName: 'wiki',       // Must match the name in the Statsig console\n    defaultValue: false,       // Used when Statsig is unreachable or flag is unconfigured\n  },\n};\n```\n\nThe `statsigName` must exactly match the feature gate name created in the Statsig console. The `defaultValue` is the fallback used when the flag cannot be fetched (e.g., no network, Statsig outage).\n\nTo add a new flag:\n1. Create the gate in the Statsig console (Feature Gates → Create New Gate, snake_case name)\n2. Add the entry to `FactoryFeatureFlags` in `packages/common/src/feature-flags/constants.ts`\n3. Use the flag in the relevant surface (see below)\n\n## Dynamic configs\n\nBeyond boolean flags, Statsig dynamic configs carry typed configuration objects. Schemas are defined alongside the flag constants and validated with Zod:\n\n```typescript\nexport const DEFAULT_MODEL_OVERRIDE = 'default_model_override' as const;\n\nexport const DYNAMIC_CONFIG_SCHEMAS = {\n  [DEFAULT_MODEL_OVERRIDE]: z.object({\n    modelId: z.string().optional(),\n    reasoningEffort: z.enum([...]).optional(),\n  }),\n  // ...\n};\n```\n\nDynamic configs are used for things like the default model override, PSA banners, minimum extension version requirements, and CLI banner messages.\n\n## Checking flags on the frontend\n\nWrap components in `FeatureFlagProvider` (done at the app root in `packages/frontend/src/features/feature-flags/FeatureFlag.provider.tsx`). The provider fetches flags from the Factory API via `useQueryOrganizationUser` and merges them with defaults.\n\nUse the `useFeatureFlagValue` hook in components:\n\n```typescript\nimport { useFeatureFlagValue } from '@/featureFlags';\nimport { FactoryFeatureFlags } from '@factory/common/feature-flags';\n\nfunction WikiPage() {\n  const isWikiEnabled = useFeatureFlagValue(FactoryFeatureFlags.Wiki);\n  if (!isWikiEnabled) return <WikiUnavailableContent />;\n  // ...\n}\n```\n\n`useFeatureFlagValue` applies a local override layer (from `featureFlagOverridesAtom`) before returning the remote value, allowing developers to test flags locally without changing Statsig.\n\nFor dynamic config values, use `useDynamicConfigValue`:\n\n```typescript\nconst banner = useDynamicConfigValue(FACTORY_PSA_BANNER);\n```\n\n## Checking flags on the backend\n\n```typescript\nimport { getFeatureFlagInstance } from '@/features/feature-flags/server';\nimport { FactoryFeatureFlags } from '@factory/common/feature-flags';\n\nconst featureFlags = await getFeatureFlagInstance();\nconst isEnabled = await featureFlags.checkFlag(\n  FactoryFeatureFlags.Wiki,\n  firestoreOrgId\n);\n```\n\n`getFeatureFlagInstance()` initializes a Statsig server client as a singleton (using a `once()` wrapper). All server-side checks require a `firestoreOrgId` to enable per-organization targeting. If initialization fails or times out (5-second limit), the call falls back to `defaultValue`.\n\n## Checking flags in the CLI\n\nThe CLI fetches feature flags at startup via `fetchFeatureFlags` from `@factory/services/feature-flags`. The `useFeatureFlagValue` hook in `apps/cli/src/feature-flags/hooks.ts` wraps the fetched values for use in React components (the TUI). Non-React CLI code accesses flags through `FeatureFlagService` (`apps/cli/src/services/FeatureFlagService.ts`).\n\n## Statsig environments\n\nStatsig gates are evaluated against a tier that maps to the deployment environment:\n\n| Factory environment | Statsig tier |\n|---|---|\n| `localhost` | `development` |\n| `dev` (staging) | `staging` |\n| `production` | `production` |\n\nConfigure gates in the Statsig console against the correct tier to avoid enabling production features in staging.\n\n## Local override menu\n\nIn development and staging, a \"DEV\" menu appears at the bottom right of the web app. It lists all flags with their current state and lets developers toggle them locally. Overrides are stored in `featureFlagOverridesAtom` (Jotai atom) and are not persisted to Statsig.\n\n## Integration points\n\n| Component | Relationship |\n|---|---|\n| `packages/common/src/feature-flags/constants.ts` | Authoritative flag and dynamic config registry |\n| `packages/frontend/src/features/feature-flags/hooks.ts` | `useFeatureFlagValue`, `useDynamicConfigValue` hooks |\n| `packages/frontend/src/features/feature-flags/FeatureFlag.provider.tsx` | React context provider |\n| `apps/backend/src/features/feature-flags/server.ts` | Server-side `getFeatureFlagInstance()` |\n| `apps/cli/src/services/FeatureFlagService.ts` | CLI feature flag access |\n| `apps/backend/src/app/api/feature-flags/` | API endpoint that serves flags to the frontend |\n| [features/llm-integration.md](./llm-integration.md) | Model routing flags (`UseAnthropicBedrock`, model-specific gates) |\n| [features/wiki-generation.md](./wiki-generation.md) | `Wiki` flag gates the wiki viewer |\n| [features/automations.md](./automations.md) | `Automations` flag gates the automations feature |\n",
