            "content": "# Skills system\n\n**Active contributors**: Arman Bolat, shashank-factory, Luke Alvoeiro, theo\n\n## Purpose\n\nA skill is a directory containing a `SKILL.md` file (with YAML frontmatter) and optional supporting files (scripts, schemas, checklists). Skills teach Droid a reusable workflow or domain-specific context. When a skill is active, its markdown content is injected into the agent's system context before the conversation begins.\n\nSkills are distinct from MCP tools: skills provide *instructions and context* to the LLM, while MCP tools provide *executable functions*. See [features/skills.md](../../features/skills.md) for the cross-cutting feature description.\n\n## Skill file format\n\n```markdown\n---\nname: summarize-diff\ndescription: Summarize the staged git diff in 3-5 bullets. Use when the user asks for a summary of pending changes.\nenabled: true          # optional, defaults to true\nuserInvocable: true    # optional, defaults to true\n---\n\n# Summarize Diff\n\n## Instructions\n\n1. Run `git diff --staged`.\n2. Summarize the changes in 3-5 bullets, focusing on user-visible behavior.\n3. Call out any migrations, risky areas, or tests that should be run.\n```\n\nKey frontmatter fields:\n\n| Field | Default | Purpose |\n|---|---|---|\n| `name` | (required) | Unique identifier; becomes the slash command name |\n| `description` | (required) | One-to-two sentence summary; used by Droid for skill discovery |\n| `enabled` | `true` | Whether the skill is loaded |\n| `userInvocable` | `true` | Whether the skill is registered as a `/name` slash command |\n\nA skill is **always a directory**. The directory may also contain scripts (`.sh`, `.py`), schemas, checklists, environment templates, and a `references.md`.\n\n## Skill locations\n\n| Scope | Path | Sharing |\n|---|---|---|\n| Project | `<repo>/.factory/skills/<skill-name>/SKILL.md` | Committed to git, shared with teammates |\n| Personal | `~/.factory/skills/<skill-name>/SKILL.md` | Local to the machine, private |\n\nBoth locations are merged by `SettingsManager` with project skills taking precedence on name conflicts.\n\n## Built-in skills\n\n`src/skills/builtin/constants.ts` contains large string constants for the bundled built-in skills. These are hardcoded into the CLI binary and registered alongside user skills. Examples include `tuistory` (TUI automation) and `agent-browser` (browser automation).\n\n`src/skills/builtin/index.ts` exposes these constants for registration at startup.\n\n## How skills become slash commands\n\n```mermaid\ngraph LR\n    A[SettingsManager.getResolvedSettings] --> B[skills array]\n    B --> C{enabled && userInvocable?}\n    C -- yes --> D[SkillCommandsLoader.registerAll]\n    D --> E[commandRegistry.register slash command]\n    E --> F[/skill-name available in TUI]\n```\n\n`src/commands/skills/SkillCommandsLoader.ts` filters to skills where `validationResult.valid && metadata.enabled && metadata.userInvocable`, then calls `buildSlashCommandsForSkills()` to create `SlashCommand` objects. These are registered in the global `commandRegistry`. Existing command names are never overwritten.\n\nWhen a user types `/skill-name` in the TUI, the slash command injects the skill content into the conversation context and runs the agent.\n\n`src/commands/skills/SkillCommandsLoader.ts` registration happens during `import('@/commands')` in `src/main.tsx` — early in TUI startup.\n\n## Invoking a skill\n\n### Via slash command (TUI)\n\n```\n/skill-name [optional arguments]\n```\n\n### Via `/skills` command\n\nThe `/skills` slash command lists all registered skills. It also provides a filtered view and can be used to navigate to a skill.\n\n### Programmatically (exec mode)\n\nSkill context can be embedded in the system prompt by calling the skill's instructions directly as part of the prompt, since exec mode has no slash command UX.\n\n## Creating a skill: `/create-skill`\n\nThe `/create-skill <description>` slash command triggers the skill creation workflow:\n\n1. The command (`src/commands/create-skill.ts`) opens a guided overlay in the TUI (if available) or falls back to a message-based flow.\n2. The overlay calls `getSkillCreatorMessage(description)` which constructs a multi-block message:\n   - **Instructions block** (`SYSTEM_NOTIFICATION`) — detailed research and writing instructions for the agent, including how to search past sessions, find evidence, and structure the skill.\n   - **Skills documentation reference** (`SYSTEM_REMINDER`) — the full skill format spec, best practices, and example frontmatter.\n   - **Existing skills list** (`SYSTEM_REMINDER`) — enumeration of already-registered skills to prevent duplication.\n3. The agent runs with these instructions, performing a deep survey of the codebase and past sessions before proposing and writing the skill directory.\n\n```mermaid\nsequenceDiagram\n    participant U as User\n    participant C as /create-skill command\n    participant A as AgentLoop\n    participant FS as File system\n\n    U->>C: /create-skill \"query axiom logs\"\n    C->>C: getSkillCreatorMessage(description)\n    C->>A: run with instructions + docs + existing-skills\n    A->>FS: search sessions/, read existing skills\n    A->>U: propose skill spec (evidence table)\n    A->>FS: write .factory/skills/<name>/SKILL.md\n    A->>U: suggest testing: /skills to verify\n```\n\nThe creation instructions (`src/commands/create-skill.ts`) require the agent to:\n- Search past sessions for evidence before writing anything\n- Produce a findings table with quoted citations\n- Consider what supporting scripts or schemas should accompany the SKILL.md\n- Never fabricate findings from a single session\n\n## Skill validation\n\nWhen `SettingsManager` loads skills, each skill is validated against a schema. The result is stored in `skill.validationResult`. Only skills with `validationResult.valid === true` are registered or loaded into context.\n\n## Integration points\n\n- **`SettingsManager`** (`@factory/services/settings`) — resolves skills from both personal and project directories\n- **`commandRegistry`** (`src/commands/registry`) — central registry for all slash commands\n- **`src/commands/skills/SkillCommandsLoader.ts`** — registers skills as slash commands at startup\n- **`src/commands/create-skill.ts`** — `/create-skill` command handler\n- **`src/skills/builtin/`** — built-in skill constants embedded in the binary\n\n## Entry points for modification\n\n| Goal | File |\n|---|---|\n| Change skill loading/filtering logic | `src/commands/skills/SkillCommandsLoader.ts` |\n| Change how slash commands are built from skills | `src/commands/skills/BuildSlashCommandsForSkills.ts` |\n| Change skill creation instructions | `src/commands/create-skill.ts` → `getSkillCreatorMessage()` |\n| Add or update a built-in skill | `src/skills/builtin/constants.ts` |\n| Change skill validation schema | `@factory/services/settings` (SettingsManager) |\n\n## Related pages\n\n- [features/skills.md](../../features/skills.md) — Skills feature cross-cutting description\n- [apps/cli/index.md](./index.md) — CLI overview\n- [apps/cli/session-management.md](./session-management.md) — Session context in which skills run\n- [overview/glossary.md](../../overview/glossary.md) — Skill definition\n",
