            "content": "# How to contribute\n\nThis section covers everything needed to pick up work, write code, get it reviewed, and land it in the repo.\n\n## Work pickup process\n\n1. **Find or create a Linear ticket** — all non-trivial work starts with a `FAC-*` ticket. Pick up an existing ticket from the backlog, or create one for work you're driving.\n2. **Create a branch** — branch from `dev` using the naming format `<handle>/<ticket>-short-description`, e.g. `alice/FAC-1234-add-webhook-handler`. Branch names must be ≤ 32 characters and use only letters, numbers, hyphens, and slashes.\n3. **Make changes, test locally** — run the relevant checks before pushing (see [development workflow](./development-workflow.md) and [testing](./testing.md)).\n4. **Open a PR targeting `dev`** — follow the PR conventions below.\n5. **Respond to review** — address comments, push fixups, re-request review.\n6. **Merge** — squash-merge once approved and CI passes. The Linear ticket closes automatically if the PR description includes `Closes FAC-*`.\n\n## PR conventions\n\n**Title** uses Conventional Commits format:\n\n```\ntype(scope): description\n```\n\nAllowed types: `feat`, `fix`, `docs`, `refactor`, `test`, `chore`, `perf`, `ci`, `build`, `style`, `security`, `revert`.\n\nScope is a workspace directory name from `apps/*` or `packages/*`, or `monorepo`. Examples:\n\n```\nfeat(cli): add wiki-upload command\nfix(frontend): resolve sidebar scroll overflow\nchore(monorepo): update turbo to 2.7\n```\n\n**Description** must reference a Linear ticket (`Closes FAC-1234` or `Part of FAC-1234`). `chore` and `revert` PRs are exempt.\n\n**Template** (`.github/pull_request_template.md`):\n\n- **Description** — what changed and why\n- **Related issue** — `Closes FAC-*` or `Part of FAC-*`\n- **Potential risk & impact** — list risks and affected features; use `N/A` only if truly none\n- **How has this been tested** — describe testing steps and include screenshots or recordings\n\nCI validates the title format, branch name, and Linear ticket link on every PR targeting `dev`.\n\n## Review expectations\n\n- PRs should be scoped: one feature or fix per PR keeps reviews focused.\n- Reviewers aim to respond within one business day.\n- Address all blocking comments before merging; non-blocking (nitpick) comments can be deferred.\n- Use the GitHub \"Request review\" button after pushing updates — don't assume reviewers re-check automatically.\n\n## Definition of done\n\nA change is done when:\n\n- [ ] All CI checks pass (lint, typecheck, tests, PR conventions)\n- [ ] At least one approval from a code owner\n- [ ] No unresolved blocking review comments\n- [ ] Linear ticket is linked and will close on merge\n- [ ] Any necessary follow-up tickets are created\n\n## Code ownership\n\nThe repo uses CODEOWNERS (`.github/CODEOWNERS`). Changes to certain paths auto-request review from the relevant team. If CI flags a missing review, check whether your change touches an owned path.\n\n---\n\n## Pages in this section\n\n- [Development workflow](./development-workflow.md) — branch, code, test, PR, merge cycle\n- [Testing](./testing.md) — unit tests, E2E tests, coverage\n- [Debugging](./debugging.md) — logs, common errors, troubleshooting\n- [Tooling](./tooling.md) — build system, linting, formatting, type checking\n- [Patterns and conventions](./patterns-and-conventions.md) — coding patterns and error handling\n\n## Related\n\n- [Getting started](../overview/getting-started.md) — setup and install instructions\n- [Architecture](../overview/architecture.md) — repo structure and system design\n",
