            "content": "# Glossary\n\nProject-specific terms and concepts used throughout the Factory platform and this wiki.\n\n## Core concepts\n\n**Droid**\nThe AI software engineering agent. The primary product. Users interact with Droid via the CLI (`apps/cli`), web app (`apps/web`), or desktop app (`apps/desktop`).\n\n**factoryd**\nThe daemon process (`apps/daemon`) that manages agent sessions. Runs as a background service, either bundled with the desktop app or deployed on a remote CDE. The CLI and web clients connect to it over WebSocket JSON-RPC.\n\n**Session**\nA single conversation with Droid. A session has a message history, associated files, and a working directory. Sessions persist across restarts and can be resumed, forked, or searched.\n\n**Mission**\nA long-running autonomous task assigned to Droid. In mission mode (also called \"AGI mode\" or \"large task decomposition\"), Droid breaks a high-level goal into subtasks and executes them semi-autonomously. See [missions feature](../features/missions.md).\n\n**Skill**\nA reusable prompt file (Markdown) that gives Droid specialized context and instructions for a particular task (e.g., writing unit tests, creating PRs, running evals). Skills are stored in `.factory/skills/` and invoked via the skills menu or `@skill-name` shorthand. See [skills feature](../features/skills.md).\n\n**Tool**\nA capability that Droid can invoke during a session: reading/writing files, executing shell commands, searching code, browsing the web, etc. Tools are defined in `@factory/droid-core/src/tools/`. External tools are registered via MCP.\n\n**MCP (Model Context Protocol)**\nA protocol that allows external servers to register additional tools with the Droid agent. Configured in `.factory/mcp.json`. The `McpHub` in `apps/cli/src/mcp/McpHub.ts` manages connections to MCP servers.\n\n**ACP (Agent Communication Protocol)**\nThe internal protocol used for communication between CLI components and the daemon, based on JSON-RPC 2.0 over WebSocket.\n\n## Modes\n\n**Interactive mode (TUI)**\nThe default CLI mode. Renders a terminal UI using Ink (React). The main `app.tsx` entry point handles this mode.\n\n**Exec mode**\nNon-interactive CLI mode invoked via `droid exec`. Uses Commander.js to parse flags and runs the agent loop without a TUI. Used in automated pipelines and scripts.\n\n**Spec mode**\nA CLI mode where Droid presents a plan (specification) before executing — showing the user what it intends to do and waiting for approval. Used to reduce unexpected changes in sensitive workflows.\n\n**Daemon mode**\nWhen the CLI itself acts as a daemon (spawned by another CLI process). The CLI entry point detects this and skips TUI initialization.\n\n## Infrastructure\n\n**CDE (Cloud Development Environment)**\nA cloud-hosted development environment where the daemon runs remotely. Factory uses E2B sandboxes for cloud CDEs.\n\n**E2B**\nThe sandboxing platform used for cloud CDEs. E2B provides isolated Linux environments where the daemon and agent run.\n\n**Relay**\nA proxy/relay service (`apps/signal`, `apps/relay`, `apps/bridge`) that routes WebSocket connections between clients and daemon instances in cloud environments.\n\n## Development\n\n**BYOK (Bring Your Own Key)**\nA mode that lets users supply their own LLM API keys instead of using Factory's hosted LLM proxy. Configured via CLI settings.\n\n**Warmup**\nA session initialization optimization that pre-fetches context (repository structure, git status, etc.) before the user sends a message, reducing perceived latency.\n\n**Compaction**\nSummarizing older parts of a conversation to stay within LLM context limits. Handled by the `compaction/` hooks in `apps/cli/src/hooks/`.\n\n**AskUser tool**\nA special tool that allows Droid to ask the user a clarifying question mid-task, with structured multiple-choice options. Controlled by the `ask_user` feature flag.\n\n## Packages and naming\n\n**@factory/core-ui**\nThe mandatory design system package. All UI in web apps must use its primitives (Box, Flex, Button, Input, etc.) — never raw HTML elements.\n\n**@factory/common**\nShared TypeScript types, enums, API type definitions, and feature flag constants. The single source of truth for cross-package contracts.\n\n**@factory/droid-core**\nThe AI agent core library. Contains tool definitions, LLM streaming utilities, message type handling, and prompt construction.\n\n**@factory/frontend**\nShared React features used by `apps/web` and `apps/desktop`: sessions, auth, settings, wiki, and more.\n\n**@factory/services**\nService layer with business logic, including plugin management, session search, and settings.\n\n**@factory/runtime**\nRuntime utilities: authentication/credential storage (using keytar), environment detection.\n\n## External integrations\n\n**WorkOS**\nThe authentication provider. Handles user login, SSO, and organization management.\n\n**Orb**\nThe billing platform for subscription management.\n\n**Statsig**\nFeature flag platform. Feature flags are defined in `packages/common/src/feature-flags/constants.ts` and checked via Statsig's SDK.\n\n**Linear**\nThe issue tracker. PRs reference Linear ticket numbers (e.g., `Closes FAC-1234`).\n",
