            "content": "# Patterns and conventions\n\nThis page covers coding patterns, architectural conventions, and cross-cutting concerns used throughout the Factory monorepo.\n\n## Error handling\n\nThe repo uses a custom error hierarchy from `@factory/logging/errors`. Never throw a bare `Error`.\n\n```typescript\nimport {\n  MetaError,\n  ResponseError400BadRequest,\n  ResponseError404NotFound,\n  ResponseError429RateLimitExceeded,\n} from '@factory/logging/errors';\nimport { logInfo, logWarn, logException } from '@factory/logging';\n```\n\n**Rules:**\n- Internal errors → `MetaError`\n- HTTP errors → matching `ResponseErrorXXX` class\n- Log context before risky calls with `logInfo`/`logWarn`, not after\n- If you call `logException`, you handle the error locally (no rethrow)\n- If you rethrow, don't log — just add breadcrumbs and rethrow\n- Preserve the original stack; only create new error objects when semantics change\n\n```typescript\n// Good: breadcrumb + rethrow\nlogInfo('Fetching session', { sessionId });\nconst session = await getSession(sessionId);\n\n// Good: handled locally\ntry {\n  await riskyOperation();\n} catch (err) {\n  logException(err, 'riskyOperation failed');\n  return fallbackValue;\n}\n\n// Bad: bare Error\nthrow new Error('Something went wrong');\n```\n\nSee `docs/error-handling.md` for the full specification.\n\n## File organization\n\nESLint enforces these rules across all packages:\n\n- **Enums** go in `enums.ts` files — never in component or service files\n- **Types** go in `types.ts` files\n- **API types** go in `packages/common/src/api/{service}/types.ts`\n- Use **absolute imports** — `@factory/...` or `@/...` — never relative paths like `../../utils`\n- No `require()` — ES6 `import` only\n\n```typescript\n// Good\nimport { SessionStatus } from '@factory/common/session';\nimport { useSessionService } from '@/services/SessionService';\n\n// Bad\nimport { SessionStatus } from '../../common/session';\nconst utils = require('./utils');\n```\n\n## UI development\n\nAll UI in React apps must use `@factory/core-ui` primitives — never raw HTML elements:\n\n```typescript\n// Good\nimport { Box, Button, Text } from '@factory/core-ui';\n<Box padding={2}><Button onClick={handleClick}>Submit</Button></Box>\n\n// Bad\n<div style={{ padding: '8px' }}><button onClick={handleClick}>Submit</button></div>\n```\n\nColors come from the semantic color system — never hardcoded hex values:\n\n```typescript\nimport { colors } from '@factory/core-ui';\n// colors.semantics.background, colors.semantics.text.primary, etc.\n```\n\nSee `docs/ui-development.md` and `docs/frontend.md` for the full UI guide.\n\n## Redux state selection\n\nIn web apps using Redux Toolkit, select state precisely and avoid selecting entire slices:\n\n```typescript\n// Good: precise selection\nconst messageTree = useSelector((state: RootState) => state.assembly.messageTree);\n\n// Bad: broad selection\nconst { messageTree } = useSelector((state: RootState) => state.assembly);\n```\n\nMemoize expensive selectors with `createSelector` from Redux Toolkit.\n\n## React component conventions\n\nFrom `docs/frontend.md`:\n\n- Components should be as stateless as possible\n- Maximum 200-300 lines per component; extract into subcomponents\n- Pull repeated state/effect logic into custom hooks\n- No utility functions inside component files — put them in `utils/`\n- Use CSS-driven interactions over component state where possible\n\n## Feature flags\n\nFeature flags are defined in `packages/common/src/feature-flags/constants.ts` and checked via Statsig.\n\n```typescript\n// In React components\nimport { useFeatureFlagValue } from '@/featureFlags';\nimport { FactoryFeatureFlags } from '@factory/common/feature-flags';\n\nconst isEnabled = useFeatureFlagValue(FactoryFeatureFlags.MyNewFeature);\n```\n\n```typescript\n// In backend API routes\nimport { getFeatureFlagInstance } from '@/features/feature-flags/server';\n\nconst featureFlags = await getFeatureFlagInstance();\nconst isEnabled = await featureFlags.checkFlag(FactoryFeatureFlags.MyNewFeature, orgId);\n```\n\nSee `docs/feature-flags.md` for full instructions including how to add new flags.\n\n## API type definitions\n\nAll new API endpoints require types in `@factory/common`:\n\n```\npackages/common/src/api/{service}/types.ts\n```\n\nThis shared contract ensures type safety between backend and clients without duplication.\n\n## Monorepo filtering\n\nAlways use `--` before `--filter` when running Turborepo commands via npm scripts:\n\n```bash\n# Correct\nnpm run test -- --filter=@factory/common\n\n# Wrong (npm eats the flag, runs everything)\nnpm run test --filter=@factory/common\n```\n\n## Testing conventions\n\n- Frontend tests need `/** @jest-environment jsdom */` at the file top\n- Mock at the module level with `jest.requireActual` to preserve real behavior:\n\n```typescript\njest.mock('./module', () => ({\n  ...jest.requireActual('./module'),\n  functionToMock: jest.fn(),\n}));\n\nbeforeEach(() => jest.resetAllMocks());\n```\n\n- For singletons, use `jest.resetModules()` and dynamic imports:\n\n```typescript\nbeforeEach(() => jest.resetModules());\nit('test', async () => {\n  const { getService } = await import('./service');\n});\n```\n\nSee `docs/unit-tests.md` for the full testing guide.\n\n## CLI-specific patterns\n\nThe CLI uses React hooks to manage all state and side effects. Key hooks:\n\n| Hook | Purpose |\n|---|---|\n| `useAgent` | Manages the overall agent conversation state |\n| `useLLMStreaming` | Handles streaming LLM responses, tool calls, compaction |\n| `createLLMStreamingCore` | Core streaming logic shared with exec mode |\n| `useChatKeyboardInput` | Full terminal keyboard input handling |\n| `useToolExecution` | Executes tools, handles confirmation, cancellation |\n\nThe `AgentLoop` class in `apps/cli/src/core/AgentLoop.ts` orchestrates the conversation loop used in exec mode.\n\n## Logging\n\nUse `@factory/logging` for all log calls:\n\n```typescript\nimport { logInfo, logWarn, logException } from '@factory/logging';\n\nlogInfo('Processing request', { requestId, userId });\nlogWarn('Rate limit approaching', { remaining });\n```\n\nNever use `console.log` in production code. The CLI patches `console.*` in `apps/cli/src/utils/patch-console.ts` to redirect to the logging system.\n\n## Git commit conventions\n\nPR titles use Conventional Commits format:\n```\ntype(scope): description\n```\n- Types: `feat`, `fix`, `docs`, `refactor`, `test`, `chore`\n- Scope: workspace name (e.g., `cli`, `frontend`, `backend`, `monorepo`)\n- Example: `feat(cli): add wiki-upload command`\n\nInclude a Linear ticket in the PR description: `Closes FAC-1234`.\n",
